ard rate per hour. This variance measures the difference between the actual hours worked and the budgeted hours, using the standard fixed overhead absorption rate per hour.\n\nAn example calculation of the fixed overhead capacity variance is given as: 119,680 - 125,400 = $5,720 (Adverse). This indicates an adverse variance, meaning the actual labor hours were less than the budgeted labor hours, resulting in a lower capacity to absorb fixed overheads.\n\nA favorable variance, on the other hand, would indicate that the firm has increased capacity to absorb fixed overheads due to more actual labor hours than budgeted. The concept is often tested in quizzes involving the calculation of fixed overhead capacity variance given budgeted and actual production and labor hours.", "\"FIXED OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\":\"Fixed Overhead Efficiency Variance\" is calculated by comparing the actual labor hours worked with the standard labor hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. The formula for this calculation is: Fixed Overhead Efficiency Variance = (Actual labor hours - Standard labor hours for actual output) x Standard rate per hour. This variance measures the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours allowed for the actual output, using the standard fixed overhead absorption rate per hour.", "\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCE\":\"Sales Volume Variance\" is a financial metric that measures the difference between the actual quantity of units sold and the budgeted quantity expected to be sold, valued at the standard contribution per unit. It can be calculated using several formulas, including:\n\n1. Sales volume variance = (Actual quantity sold - Budgeted quantity sold) x Standard selling price\n2. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales - Budgeted sales) * Standard profit per unit\n3. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales quantity - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution per unit\n4. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution\n\nThis variance indicates whether more or fewer units were sold than expected and shows the effect on profit of selling more or less than the budgeted quantity. Additionally, sales volume variance can be analyzed into a market size (planning) variance and a market share (operational) variance.", "\"SALES PRICE VARIANCE\":\"Sales Price Variance\" is a financial metric used to measure the impact on profit due to differences between the actual selling price and the standard selling price. It is calculated by comparing the actual price to the standard price, multiplied by the actual volume sold. The formula for sales price variance is (Actual Selling Price - Standard Selling Price) * Actual Quantity Sold. This variance highlights the effect on profit when products are sold at prices higher or lower than the standard price.", "\"MATERIALS PRICE VARIANCE\":Materials price variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost, multiplied by the actual quantity used or purchased. It is calculated by comparing the actual materials purchased at the actual price with the actual materials purchased at the standard price. This variance helps in understanding whether materials were purchased at a higher or lower price than expected, thereby indicating the impact of price changes on material costs.\n\nFor example, for Material X, if the actual cost is $27,000 and the standard cost is $29,700, the resulting variance is favorable by $2,700. Conversely, for Material Y, if the actual cost is $11,000 and the standard cost is $10,600, the variance is adverse by $400. The total materials price variance in this case would be $2,300 favorable.\n\nAdditionally, there are different types of price variances such as Traditional Price/Rate Variance, Planning Price Variance, and Operational Price Variance. The Traditional Price/Rate Variance is calculated as the actual quantity multiplied by the actual price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the standard price. The Planning Price Variance is the actual quantity multiplied by the original standard price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the revised standard price. The Operational Price Variance is the actual quantity multiplied by the actual price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the revised standard price.", "\"MATERIALS USAGE VARIANCE\":\"Materials Usage Variance\" is a metric used to measure the efficiency of material usage in production. It is calculated by comparing the actual quantity of materials used to the standard quantity expected for the actual output, and then multiplying the difference by the standard cost per unit. Specifically, the formula is: Materials usage variance = (Actual materials used - Standard quantity for actual output) * Standard cost per kg.\n\nFor example, in the case of Material X, the actual quantity used was 9,900 kg, while the standard quantity was 10,000 kg, resulting in a favorable variance of $300. Conversely, for Material Y, the actual quantity used was 5,300 kg compared to a standard quantity of 5,000 kg, leading to an adverse variance of $600. Overall, the total materials usage variance amounted to $300 adverse.\n\nThis variance helps in understanding the efficiency of material usage by highlighting the differences between actual and expected material consumption, thereby providing insights into potential areas for improvement in the production process.", "\"LABOUR RATE VARIANCE\":Labour rate variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual hourly wage rate paid and the standard rate expected to be paid, multiplied by the actual hours worked. It is calculated by comparing the actual hours paid at the actual rate with the actual hours paid at the standard rate. This can be expressed mathematically as (Standard Rate - Actual Rate) * Actual Hours paid. Essentially, it evaluates the effect of the actual labor rate differing from the standard labor rate, using the actual hours worked. The quiz on labour rate variance involves calculating this variance given budgeted and actual labour costs and hours.", "\"IDLE TIME VARIANCE\":\"Idle time variance is calculated as the difference between hours paid and hours worked, multiplied by the standard hourly rate.\"", "\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\":Labour efficiency variance is a measure used to evaluate the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours expected for actual production, multiplied by the standard hourly wage rate. It is calculated by comparing the actual labour hours worked with the standard hours for the actual output, and then multiplying this difference by the standard cost per hour. This variance helps in assessing the efficiency of labour by highlighting the impact of deviations in actual hours worked from the standard hours, using the standard labour rate.", "\"VARIABLE OVERHEAD RATE VARIANCE\":Variable Overhead Rate Variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual variable overhead costs incurred and the expected (or standard) variable overhead costs based on labor hours worked. The calculation can be expressed in several ways, but fundamentally, it involves comparing the actual variable overhead cost to the standard cost derived from labor hours and the standard rate. The formula for Variable Overhead Rate Variance is:\n\nVariable Overhead Rate Variance = Actual variable overhead cost - (Labor hours worked x Standard variable overhead rate per hour).\n\nAlternatively, it can also be expressed as:\n\nVariable Overhead Rate Variance = (Standard Rate - Actual Rate) x Actual Hours worked.\n\nIn essence, this variance helps in understanding how well a company is managing its variable overhead costs relative to its labor hours and standard rates.", "\"VARIABLE OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\":\"Variable Overhead Efficiency Variance\" is calculated by comparing the actual labor hours worked with the standard labor hours for actual production, multiplied by the standard variable overhead rate per hour. The formula can be expressed as: Variable Overhead Efficiency Variance = (Labor hours worked - Standard labor hours for actual production) x Standard variable overhead rate per hour. This variance represents the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours expected to be worked, multiplied by the standard variable overhead rate.", "\"OPERATING STATEMENT RECONCILIATION\":\"The operating statement is a formal reconciliation of budgeted profit to actual profit under absorption costing. It includes reconciling items such as individual variances for sales margin, materials, labor, and overheads.\"", "\"LABOUR IDLE TIME VARIANCE\":\"Labour idle time variance is calculated as (Standard Hours - Actual Hours paid) * Standard Rate.\"", "\"MARGINAL COSTING OPERATING STATEMENT\":\"A pro-forma operating statement under marginal costing includes budgeted contribution, sales margin variances, standard profit on actual sales, cost variances, and actual profit.\"", "\"INVENTORY VALUATION AT ACTUAL COST\":\"Inventory valued at actual cost includes sales minus costs plus closing inventory. This method carries forward some of the current period's production cost variances in the inventory value.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}